## Readability and Accessibility of Results

We have already introduced the concepts of accessibility and readability in the context of designing Microsoft Word documents. As we said at the time, “you may have never thought about it in these terms, but writing a document is an act of design.” Well, guess what, creating a professional and usable Microsoft Excel Workbook is also an act of design. When sophisticated end-users open Excel to perform some analysis, they have already conceptualized what they want to accomplish – the results of the analysis – and how to accomplish it – the algorithm they develop to analyze the data.
We will discuss more fully the process of designing a Worksheet in terms of inputs, processing and outputs, in a later chapter. For now we want to focus on the design of the results sheet. In fact, thinking about who will access the results and what those results should look like is the first step in the design of your Workbook. As with any other report, like the ones you wrote with Microsoft Word, you have to make sure that your results are accessible and readable. In the context of an Excel results page:
  - Accessibility refers to the visual layout and navigation of your page. You should think about the degree of knowledge your intended audience has about your analysis. If you are sharing your Workbook with your boss for example, you can expect her to be very familiar with the language you use, the data you have processed in your Worksheet, the variables and metrics you use to display your results, the relationships between these metrics, and the objectives of your analysis. For example, if you are working in the finance department of a large Pizza chain, you will likely be processing pizza orders by store, revenues and cost figures, and the like. Your boss would be very familiar with all these.
Compare the above situation with one where you are creating a Worksheet that you will be using with potential partners, new employees, investors or customers who are generally unfamiliar with your business. They will likely not have intimate knowledge of your business and you should guide the readers through the analysis. For example, you should make sure to spell out any acronyms, you should visually organize your results in coherent groups, you may consider having a section of the results page with definitions and explanation of metrics.
In short, accessibility is about “stepping in your audience’s shoes” and design the visual layout and labeling of your results to be as simple and immediate as possible for them.
  - Readability refers to the understandability of your results by your intended audience. When thinking about the readability of your results remember what you learned in the context of Microsoft Word. Any element on the results page should have predictable and consistent formatting. You achieve this with the same stylistic elements you have at your disposal in Word. For example, you should select a Theme that will provide consistency of colors and styles to your Worksheet. You should be sure to use consistent formatting for labels and use font size and effects to visually separate them while signaling their relationships – similarly to how you would use styles in Microsoft Word.
As in any report, objects and elements should be self-standing. If you have a chart in your results page, you should not assume that the reader knows what it is about. The chart should have a title, the axes should be clearly labeled and have a clear scale and, potentially, a legend. You generally will not use images much, but you may consider having a logo on your results page.
While generally what you see on screen is what you get on paper when it comes to Microsoft Word documents, the same cannot be said about Microsoft Excel. Spreadsheets are generally designed for computations on screen and printing to paper is a secondary concern. However, a well designed Worksheet is one where the creator planned for printing by the user. You will often be creating Workbooks for much less sophisticated users (e.g. your boss!) and you should be prepared for them to do things that don’t fully make sense. On that note, you will learn quickly that those unsophisticated users tend to make mistakes and “break” your carefully crafted Workbooks. Thus, you should be able to protect your work and always lock cells that should not be modified.


